   <xocs:rawtext>Volume 82, number 3 CHEMICAL PHYSICS LETTERS    15 September 1981    Ni2""" HYDRATION IN PERCHLORATE AND CHLORIDE SOLUTIONS  J.R. NEWSOME, G.W. NEILSON, J.E. ENDERBY    H.H. Wills Physics Laboratory, University of Bristol. Royal Fort. Bristol BS8 1 TL, UK    and    M. SANDSTROM  Department of Inorganic Chemistry, Royal Institute of Technology, S-100 44 Stockholm, Sweden    Received 17 July 1981    The hydration of nickel ions in a 3.80 molal solution of nickel perchlorate in (heavy) water has been investigated by the  neutron first-order difference method. The coordination of water molecules around nickel ions is identical with that found  in an earlier study of a nickel chloride solution of comparable ionic strength.    In 1977, a new method to determine ion—water  coordination in a range of aqueous solutions was pro-  posed [1] . The method exploits the fact that the neu-  tron scattering length of an element depends on its iso-  topic state. By taking the Fourier transform of the dif-  ference in the thermal neutron scattering cross sections  for two ionic solutions, identical in all respects except  for the isotopic state of the cations (or the anions) a  high-resolution, real-space description of the cation-  water (or anion—water) structure is obtained. This  method, based on taking a "first-order" difference.  avoids all of the problems involved with the interpreta-  tion of single diffraction patterns [2] and in particular,  circumvents the need to correct the data for inelastic  (Placzek) effects [2] .    One early and as yet unexplained result of this work  arose from measurements made on NiCI^ solutions in  D^O. It was found that while r^o remained constant  at 2.07 ± 0.02 A as the molality was reduced from 4.41  to 0.086, r^iD increased from 2.67 to 2.80 ± 0.03 A  [3] . This result implies that the angle &lt;fi between the  plane of the water molecule and the Ni—0 axis (fig. 1)  decreases from 42 ± 8° to zero over the composition  range 